questions.question: \(\(If f\left(\frac{2 x+3}{3 x+5}\right)=x+4, x \neq \frac{-5}{3}, \frac{2}{3} and \int f(x) d x=A x+B \ln |3 x-2|+C, then 3 B-A=\)\)
questions.solution:
\(\(We have, f\left(\frac{2 x+3}{3 x+5}\right)=x+4
\begin{aligned}
& \text { Put, } \frac{2 x+3}{3 x+5}=y \Rightarrow 2 x+3=3 x y+5 y \Rightarrow x=\frac{5 y-3}{2-3 y} \\
& \therefore f(y)=\frac{5 y-3}{2-3 y}+4=\frac{5 y-3+8-12 y}{2-3 y} \Rightarrow f(y)=\frac{7 y-5}{3 x-2} \\
& \therefore \quad f(x)=\frac{7 x-5}{3 x-2} \Rightarrow \int f(x) d x=\int \frac{7 x-5}{3 x-2} d x
\end{aligned}
Put, 3 x-2=t \Rightarrow x=\frac{t+2}{3}
\begin{aligned}
d x & =\frac{d t}{3}=\frac{1}{3} \int \frac{7\left(\frac{t+2}{3}\right)-5}{t} d t \\
& =\frac{1}{9} \int \frac{7 t-1}{t} d t=\frac{7}{9} \int d t-\frac{1}{3} \int \frac{d t}{t} \\
& =\frac{7}{9} t-\frac{1}{9} \log t+C \\
& =\frac{7}{9}(3 x-2)-\frac{1}{9} \log |3 x-2|+C \\
& =\frac{7}{3} x-\frac{1}{9} \log |3 x-2|+C
\end{aligned}
Here, A=\frac{7}{3}, B=-\frac{1}{9}
\therefore \quad 3 B-A=3\left(-\frac{1}{9}\right)-\frac{7}{3}=-\frac{8}{3}\)\)

questions.question: \(\(If principal argument of z_0 satisfying |z-3| \leq \sqrt{2} and \arg (z-5 i)=\frac{-\pi}{4} simultaneously is \theta, then identify the incorrect statement?\)\)
questions.solution:
\(\(\operatorname{Arg}(z-5 i)=\frac{-\pi}{4} is a ray emanating from (0,5) and making an angle \frac{\pi}{4} from the x-axis in clockwise direction.
\Rightarrow \quad \arg [x+i(y-5)]=\frac{-\pi}{4} \Rightarrow \tan ^{-1}\left(\frac{y-5}{x}\right)=\frac{-\pi}{4}
\Rightarrow \quad y=5-x \Rightarrow \quad x+y=5
Also, \quad|z-3| \leq \sqrt{2} \Rightarrow|(x-3)+i y| \leq \sqrt{2}
\Rightarrow \quad(x-3)^2+y^2 \leq 2
\Rightarrow \quad x+y=5 touches the circle.

Let z_0 \quad be the complex number corresponding to point of contact.
Let \quad z_0=x_0+i y_0
x_0=3+\sqrt{2} \cos \frac{\pi}{4}=4
\quad y_0=\sqrt{2} \sin \frac{\pi}{4}=1
Now, \quad z_0=4+i
\quad \tan \theta=\frac{1}{4}
\begin{array}{ll}\text {Also, } & \left|z_0\right|=17 \\ \text { and } & \left|z_0-5 i\right|=|4+i-5 i|=4|1-i|=4 \sqrt{2}\end{array}\)\)

(b1→)×(a2→-a1→)b1→

Given equation of lines

r→=i^+2j^-4k^+λ(2i^+3j^+6k^), r→=3i^+3j^-5k^+μ(2i^+3j^+6k^)

Comparing with the standard form, we get 

a1→=i^+2j^-4k^, a2→=3i^+3j^-5k^, b1→=2i^+3j^+6k^

=(3i^-i^)+(3j^-2j^)+(-5k^+4k^)=2i^+j^-k^
Now, b1→×(a2→-a1→)=i^j^k^23621-1
⇒[i^(-3-6)-j^(-2-12)+k^(2-6)]=-9i^+14j^-4k^

Magnitude of b1→

=-9i^+14j^-4k^7=2937

questions.question: \(\(If the wavelength of the first line of the Balmer series of hydrogen is 6561 Å, find the wavelength of the second line of the series.?\)\)
questions.solution:
\(\(The wavelength of spectral line in Balmer series is given by \frac{1}{\lambda}=\mathrm{R}\left[\frac{1}{2^{2}}-\frac{1}{\mathrm{n}^{2}}\right]
For first line of Balmer series, n=3
\begin{aligned}
&\Rightarrow \frac{1}{\lambda_{1}}=\mathrm{R}\left[\frac{1}{2^{2}}-\frac{1}{3^{2}}\right]=\frac{5 \mathrm{R}}{36} ; \text { For second line } \mathrm{n}=4 \\
&\Rightarrow \frac{1}{\lambda_{2}}=\mathrm{R}\left[\frac{1}{2^{2}}-\frac{1}{4^{2}}\right]=\frac{3 \mathrm{R}}{16} \\
&\therefore \frac{\lambda_{2}}{\lambda_{1}}=\frac{20}{27} \Rightarrow \lambda_{2}=\frac{20}{27} \times 6561=4860
\end{aligned}\)\)

questions.question: \(\(A body has maximum range R_{1} when projected up the inclined plane. It has the maximum range R_{2} when projected down the plane with same speed as in first case. Then which of the following is maximum range (R) for it when projected at certain angle with the horizontal ground and with same speed as in previous two cases?\)\)
questions.solution:
\(\(For upward projection \mathrm{R}_{\max }=\frac{\mathrm{v}_{0}^{2}}{\mathrm{~g}(1+\sin \theta)}=\mathrm{R}_{1}
for downward projection R_{\max }=\frac{v_{0}^{2}}{g(1-\sin \theta)}=R_{2}
for projection on ground R_{\max }=\frac{v_{0}^{2}}{g}=R \therefore \frac{2}{\mathrm{R}}=\frac{1}{\mathrm{R}_{1}}+\frac{1}{\mathrm{R}_{2}} \Rightarrow \mathrm{R}=\frac{2 \mathrm{R}_{1} R_{2}}{\mathrm{R}_{1}+\mathrm{R}_{2}}\)\)

questions.question: \(\(A circular freeway entrance and exit are commonly banked to control a moving car at 14 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}. To design similar ramp for 28 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s} one should\)\)
questions.solution:
$Given, v_1=14 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s} and v_2=28 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}

As we know that, \tan \theta=\frac{v^2}{r g} \Rightarrow r=\frac{v^2}{g \tan \theta}

In the first case, r_1=\frac{v_1^2}{g \tan \theta}=\frac{(14)^2}{g \tan \theta} \ldots (i)

In the second case,

r_2=\frac{(28)^2}{g \tan \theta} [for similar ramp remains same]

r_2=\frac{(14 \times 2)^2}{g \tan \theta}=4 \frac{(14)^2}{g \tan \theta} \Rightarrow r_2=4 r_1 \quad \text { [using Eq. (i)] }

Hence, radius should be increased by factor 4 .$

questions.question: \(\(A mercury drop lies between two glass plates separated by a very small distance (see figure). Surface tension of mercury is \mathrm{T}. Radius of curvature of drop surfaces in a direction parallel to plates is \mathrm{R}. The other surfaces are flat. The excess pressure for the mercury drop is given by: \\ \)\)
questions.solution:
\(\(Excess pressure for a liquid drop is given by P_{\text {inside }}-P_{\text {outside }}=\frac{T}{R_{1}}+\frac{T}{R_{2}} i.e., Excess pressure =\frac{T}{R_{1}}+\frac{T}{R_{2}}
where R_{1} and R_{2} are radii of curvatures of the drop in two mutually perpendicular directions. In this case, \quad R_{1}=R \quad \& R_{2}=\infty
\therefore Excess pressure =\frac{T}{R}+\frac{T}{\infty}=\frac{T}{R}
\)\)

questions.question: \(\(The power of biconvex lens is 10 dioptre and the radius of curvature of each surface is 10 \mathrm{~cm}. Then the refractive index of the material of the lens is :\)\)
questions.solution:
\(\(P(\text { in dioptre })=\frac{100}{f(\text { in } \mathrm{cm})}
\therefore f=\frac{100}{10}=10 \mathrm{~cm}
According to lens maker's formula, \frac{1}{f}=(\mu-1)\left(\frac{1}{R_{1}}-\frac{1}{R_{2}}\right)
For biconvex lens, R_{1}=+R, R_{2}=-R
\therefore \quad \frac{1}{f}=(\mu-1)\left(\frac{1}{R}+\frac{1}{R}\right) ; \frac{1}{10}=(\mu-1)\left(\frac{2}{10}\right)
\Rightarrow \quad \mu=\frac{1}{2}+1=\frac{3}{2}\)\)

questions.question: \(\(A photon of wavelength 300 nm interacts with a stationary hydrogen atom in ground state. During the interaction, whole energy the photon is transferred to the electron of the atom. State which possibility is correct. (Consider, Plank constant =4 \times 10^{-15} eV_{s}, velocity of light =3 \times 10^{8} \mathrm{m} / \mathrm{s}, ionisation energy of hydrogen =13.6 \mathrm{eV} )\)\)
options: \(Electron will be knocked out of the atom\)
\(Electron will go to any excited state of the atom\)
\(Electron will go only to lirst excited state of the atom\)
\(Electron will keep orbiting in the ground state of the atom\)
questions.solution:
$The energy of the photon

\begin{aligned}

E &=\frac{h C}{\lambda} \\

&=\frac{4 \times 10^{-15} \mathrm{eVs} \times 3 \times 10^{8} \mathrm{m} / \mathrm{s}}{300 \times 10^{-9} \mathrm{m}} \\

&=\frac{4 \times 10^{2}}{300} \mathrm{eV}=\frac{4}{3} \mathrm{eV}=1.33 \mathrm{eV}

\end{aligned}

The ionisation energy is 13.6 \mathrm{eV} which is greater than energy of photon, so atom can not come into excited state and will remain in ground state$

questions.question: \(\(A simple pendulum has a time period <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math> when on the Earth’s surface and <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> when taken to a height <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>R</mi></math>, above the Earth’s surface, where <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>R</mi></math> is the radius of the Earth. The value of <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac></math> is\)\)
questions.solution:
\(\(

According to the question:

Time period of the simple pendulum on Earth's surface =T1

Time period of the simple pendulum at a height R above the Earth's surface =T2

R= Radius of the Earth

Now, the time period of a simple pendulum T,

T=2πlg

Here, l= Length of the simple pendulum

g= Accceleration due to gravity on Earth's surface.

As in both the cases, length of the simple pendulum remains same, so,

T∝1g

Relation of variation in g due to height h above the Earth's surface gh

gh=g1+hR2

Accceleration due to gravity at a height h=R,

gR=g1+RR2⇒g1+12

gR=g4

From T∝1g

T1∝1g

T2∝1gR

Take ratio of T2 : T1

T2T1=ggR

Put the value of gR in the above relation,

T2T1=gg2⇒4

T2T1=2

\)\)

questions.question: \(\(Two coils have a mutual induction 0.005 \mathrm{~H}. The current changes in the first coil according to the equation i=i_{m} \sin \omega t where i_{m}=10 \mathrm{~A} and \omega=100 \pi \mathrm{~rad} \mathrm{s}^{-1}. The maximum value of the emf induced in the second coil is :\)\)
questions.solution:
\(\(The emf induced in the second coil is
\varepsilon=M \frac{d i}{d t}
Where M is the mutual inductance of two coils, \frac{d i}{d t} is the rate of change of current in the first coil.
But \frac{d i=\frac{d}{d t}\left(i_{m} \sin \omega t\right)}{d t}=i_{m} \omega \cos \omega t \quad \therefore \omega=M i_{m} \omega \cos \omega t
For maximum value of emf induced, \cos \omega t=1
\therefore The maximum value of the emf induced is \varepsilon_{\max }=M i_{m} \omega
Here, M=0.005 H, i_{m}=10 A, \omega=100 \pi \mathrm{rad} \mathrm{s}^{-1}
\varepsilon_{\max }=(0.005 H)(10 A)(100 \pi)=5 \pi V\)\)

questions.question: \(\(The intensity of magnetization of a bar magnet is 5.0 \times 10^{4} \mathrm{Am}^{-1}. The magnetic length and the area of cross-section of the magnet are 12 \mathrm{cm} and 1 \mathrm{cm}^{2} respectively. The magnitude of magnetic moment of this bar magnet is (in SI unit) M, find 10M.\)\)
questions.solution:
$We know that Intensity of magnetisation

I=\frac{M}{V}

[where M= magnetic moment, V= volume]

So

\begin{aligned}

M=I V &=5.0 \times 10^{4} \times \frac{12}{100} \times \frac{1}{(100)^{2}} \\

&=60 \times 10^{4} \times 10^{-6}=0.6 \mathrm{Am}^{2}

\end{aligned}$

questions.question: \(\(The densities of two solid spheres <math><mi mathvariant="normal">A</mi></math> and <math><mi mathvariant="normal">B</mi></math> of the same radii <math><mi mathvariant="normal">R</mi></math> vary with radial distance <math><mi mathvariant="normal">r</mi></math> as <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">ρ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">A</mi></mrow></msub><mfenced separators="|"><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">r</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">k</mi><mfenced separators="|"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">R</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math> and <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">ρ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">B</mi></mrow></msub><mfenced separators="|"><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">r</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">k</mi><msup><mrow><mfenced separators="|"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">R</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></math> , respectively, where <math><mi mathvariant="normal">k</mi></math> is a constant. The moments of inertia of the individual spheres about axes passing through their centres are <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">I</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">A</mi></mrow></msub></math> and <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">I</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">B</mi></mrow></msub></math> , respectively. If <math><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">I</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">B</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">I</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">A</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow></mfrac></math> , the value of <math><mi mathvariant="normal">n</mi></math> is\)\)
questions.solution:
\(\(

The moment of inertia of a hollow sphere shell in terms of mass and radius of the shell is, I0=23mr2. Here, for sphere A:

questions.question:
\(\(

Assertion: PbO2 is an oxidising agent and reduced to PbO.

Reason: Stability of Pb(II)>Pb(IV) on account of inert pair effect.

\)\)
options: \(Both Assertion and Reason are true and Reason is the correct explanation of Assertion.\)
\(Both Assertion and Reason are true but Reason is NOT the correct explanation of Assertion.\)
\(Assertion is true but Reason is false.\)
\(Assertion is false but Reason is true.\)
questions.solution:
\(\(

Due to inert pair effect Pb has four electrons in its valence shell but it shows +2 oxidation state. In other words due to inert pair effect +2 oxidation state is more stable than +4 of Pb.

So, both Assertion and Reason are true and Reason is the correct explanation of Assertion.

\)\)

questions.question: \(\(2 \mathrm{~g} of a non-electrolyte solute (molar mass is 500 \mathrm{~g} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1} ) was dissolved in 57.3 \mathrm{~g} of xylene. If the freezing point depression constant K_f of xylene is 4.3 \mathrm{~K} \mathrm{~kg} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}. Then, the depression in freezing point of xylene is..........\)\)
questions.solution:
$\Delta T_f=K_f \times \frac{w_1 \times 1000}{w_2 \times m_1}

\begin{aligned} & w_1=\text { weight of solute } \\ & w_2=\text { weight of solvent } \\ & m_1=\text { molar mass of solute } \\ & K_f=4.3 \mathrm{~K} \mathrm{~kg} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}\end{aligned}

Now, \Delta T_f=4.3 \times \frac{2 \times 1000}{57.3 \times 500}

=\frac{17.2}{57.3}=0.30 \mathrm{~K}$

questions.question:
\(\(

The following steps are involved in the manufacturing of potassium dichromate:

What is the difference in the oxidation number of Cr between X and Y?

\)\)
questions.solution:
\(\(Check video solution for detailed explanation. Tricky question which is directly prepared from NCERT lines.

The process shown in the question is the preparation method of potassium dichromate K2Cr2O7, which is a good oxidising agent.

The chromite ore FeCr2O4 (X) is fused with sodium carbonate Na2CO3. In the presence of air, it will form sodium chromate, Na2CrO4 (Y) which will further be purified with sulphuric acid to form a solution from which the crystals of orange-coloured sodium dichromate, Na2Cr2O7 (Z) can be extracted.

4FeCr2O4+8 Na2CO3+7O2→8 Na2CrO4+2Fe2O3+8CO2

2Na2CrO4 +2H+→Na2Cr2O7 +2Na++H2O

Potassium dichromate can be obtained by reacting a solution of sodium dichromate with potassium chloride.

Na2Cr2O7 +2KCl→K2Cr2O7+2NaCl

So, X=FeCr2O4 or FeO.Cr2O3

       Y=Na2CrO4

       Z=Na2Cr2O7

The oxidation number of Cr in FeCr2O4 is +3.

The oxidation number of Cr in Na2CrO4 is +6.

The difference in the oxidation state of Cr between X and Y is 3.

\)\)

Energy of photon is given by 1240λ in nm

So here:

13.6× z21n12-1n22=1240λ1 in nm+1240λ2 in nm
13.6 ×22112-1n22=1240108.5+124030.4
13.6 ×22112-1n22=11.43+40.79
1-1n22=52.2213.6×4

n2=5

So quantum number 'n' corresponding to the excited state of He+ ion is equal to 5
